.</it> The show was about a professor who accidentally enlarged three <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../768/410768.xml">
Sea Monkeys</link> to human-size, and then had to deal with their comical ineptness in the world. In 1993, Wells starred in the sci-fi film <movie wordnetid="106613686" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../665/2199665.xml">
Fortress</link></movie>
 with <actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../099/42099.xml">
Christopher Lambert</link></actor>
.</p>
<p>

Many of Wells' roles 1990s and 2000s portrayed villains, as in the films <it><link>
Circuitry Man</link></it> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../635/34635.xml">
1990</link>), <it><link>
Kick of Death</link></it> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../601/34601.xml">
1997</link>) and <it>Starforce</it> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../548/34548.xml">
2000</link>), and  (2001). In the <it>Power Rangers</it> episodes, he played the role of Ransik, a mutant crime lord from the year 3000 who travels back in time to take over the world. In 2002, he also appeared in the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../981/12978981.xml">
Power Rangers Wild Force</link>/<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../983/12978983.xml">
Time Force</link> two-part team-up episode entitled "Reinforcements From the Future," again in the role of Ransik.</p>

